<h2>9. One last thing — about courage</h2>

<p>Standing up in front of a room and putting forward an argument that other people will push on is hard. It does not get easier the first three times. It starts to get easier somewhere around the fifth time. By the tenth, you have a baseline of composure. By the twentieth, you start to enjoy it. The course gives you eight defenses across the year. The point is the reps.</p>

<p>Underneath the moves and the protocols, defense is fundamentally an act of courage — putting your thinking forward where it can be tested, in front of people whose judgment you care about. There is no shortcut around this part. The discomfort never fully disappears; the relationship you have with the discomfort changes.</p>

<p>Your panelists are not trying to make you fail. They are trying to make your thinking sharper. The room is on your side, even when the questions are hard. Treat the defense as a gift — eight chances a year to discover what your reasoning can withstand, in a low-stakes room, with people who want you to grow. Most adults never get this. You do. Use it.</p>

